    1.🙃 Scheduling Criteria In Process Scheduling |Waiting Time|Turnaround Time| Response Time|Operatingsyst

        Scheduling criteria are used to evaluate the performance of CPU scheduling algorithms.

      ✅ 1. Waiting Time
           Time a process spends in the ready queue
           👉 Does not include execution time
           
           Waiting Time = Turnaround Time − Burst Time
           ✔️ Goal: Minimize waiting time

       ✅ 2. Turnaround Time
         Total time from process arrival to completion
         
         👉 Turnaround Time = Completion Time – Arrival Time
         
         ✔️ Goal: Minimize turnaround time    
                    
        ✅ 3. Response Time
         Time from request submission to first response (first CPU allocation)
         
        👉 Response Time = First CPU Start Time − Arrival Time
        
         ✔️ Goal: Minimize response time            
         

    2.😒 FCFS scheduling Algorithm |First Come First Serve |Convoy Effect |Process Scheduling |OS |
             Processes are executed in the order of arrival
             It is a non-preemptive scheduling algorithm

            ⚙️ Working:
                First process in ready queue gets CPU
                Runs till completion
                Next process starts

            ⚠️ Convoy Effect
                A long process blocks all shorter processes behind it
                
                👉 Causes:
                
                High waiting time
                Poor CPU & I/O utilization    


    3.😯 Shortest Job First Scheduling Algorithm || SJF || Shortest Process Next || SPN || Non Preemptive|| preemptive OS
        => non-preemptive
           Selects the process with the smallest burst time
             It is a non-preemptive scheduling algorithm           
                                
          ⚙️ Working:
               Among all ready processes, choose the one with minimum execution time
               Once started → runs till completion         

        => preemptive  

              If a new process arrives with shorter remaining time,
         👉 current process is preempted (stopped)
         CPU is given to the shortest remaining job  

         

         ✅ Advantages:
              Minimum average waiting time
              Efficient for batch systems
         ❌ Disadvantages:
              Difficult to know exact burst time
              May cause starvation (long processes wait)  


     4. 🤯 Non Preemptive and preemptive Priority Scheduling Algorithm| Operating System | OS  

        => non-preemptive
            Each process is assigned a priority
             CPU is given to the highest priority process
             It is non-preemptive → once started, process runs till completion        

        => preemptive
            Each process is assigned a priority
             CPU is given to the highest priority process
             It is preemptive → a running process can be interrupted     

         ⚠️ Problem: Starvation
              Low-priority processes may wait indefinitely
              
              👉 Solution: Aging (increase priority over time)  
    
           ✅ Advantages:
              Important tasks get CPU first
              Suitable for real-time systems
           ❌ Disadvantages:
              Starvation of low-priority processes


     5. 🤫   Round Robin Scheduling Algorithm| Preemptive | Operating System | OS

              A preemptive scheduling algorithm
               Each process gets CPU for a fixed time quantum (time slice)  

            ⚙️ Working:
                Processes are kept in a circular queue
                Each process runs for time quantum
                If not finished → moved to end of queue
                Next process gets CPU    

          ✅ Advantages:
              Fair scheduling (each gets equal time)
              Good response time for interactive systems
              
          ❌ Disadvantages:
              Too small quantum → high context switching overhead
              Too large quantum → behaves like FCFS              